00:00:22.180 --> 00:00:24.520
PROFESSOR: To begin today I want
to remind you, I need to

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:27.720
write it down on the board
at least twice, of the

00:00:27.720 --> 00:00:33.230
fundamental theorem
of calculus.

00:00:33.230 --> 00:00:38.870
We called it FTC 1 because it's
the first version of the

00:00:38.870 --> 00:00:39.620
fundamental theorem.

00:00:39.620 --> 00:00:43.150
We'll be talking about another
version, called the second

00:00:43.150 --> 00:00:44.940
version, today.

00:00:44.940 --> 00:00:58.010
And what it says is this: If F'
= f, then the integral from

00:00:58.010 --> 00:01:06.410
a to b of f (x) dx =
F ( b) - F ( a).

00:01:06.410 --> 00:01:10.750
So that's the fundamental
theorem of calculus.

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:17.820
And the way we used it last
time was, this was used to

00:01:17.820 --> 00:01:22.090
evaluate integrals.

00:01:22.090 --> 00:01:28.110
Not surprisingly, that's
how we used it.

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:35.670
But today, I want to reverse
that point of view.

00:01:35.670 --> 00:01:39.190
We're going to read the equation
backwards, and we're

00:01:39.190 --> 00:01:49.240
going to write it this way.

00:01:49.240 --> 00:02:01.110
And we're going to use f to
understand capital F. Or in

00:02:01.110 --> 00:02:04.370
other words, the derivative.

00:02:04.370 --> 00:02:07.700
To understand the function.

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:11.290
So that's the reversal
of point of view

00:02:11.290 --> 00:02:13.380
that I'd like to make.

00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:16.310
And we'll make this point
in various ways.

00:02:16.310 --> 00:02:36.460
So information about F, about
F', gives us information about

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:38.770
F. Now, since there were
questions about the mean value

00:02:38.770 --> 00:02:42.040
theorem, I'm going to illustrate
this first by

00:02:42.040 --> 00:02:45.630
making a comparison between
the fundamental theorem of

00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:50.600
calculus and the mean
value theorem.

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:55.540
So we're going to compare this
fundamental theorem of

00:02:55.540 --> 00:03:01.550
calculus with what we call
the mean value theorem.

00:03:01.550 --> 00:03:02.980
And in order to do that,
I'm going to

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:05.070
introduce a couple of notations.

00:03:05.070 --> 00:03:11.820
I'll write delta F as
F ( b ) - F ( a).

00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:17.770
And another highly imaginative
notation, delta x = b - a.

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:21.760
So here's the change in f,
there's the change in x.

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:27.420
And then, this fundamental
theorem can be written, of

00:03:27.420 --> 00:03:30.800
course, right up above
there is the formula.

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:38.110
And it's the formula for delta
F. So this is what we call the

00:03:38.110 --> 00:03:44.090
fundamental theorem
of calculus.

00:03:44.090 --> 00:03:51.810
I'm going to divide
by delta x, now.

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:56.690
And If I divide by delta x,
that's the same thing as 1 / b

00:03:56.690 --> 00:04:02.880
- a times the integral from
a to b of f ( x) dx.

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:05.110
So I've just rewritten
the formula here.

00:04:05.110 --> 00:04:11.960
And this expression here, on
the right-hand side, is a

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:13.650
fairly important one.

00:04:13.650 --> 00:04:23.370
This is the average of f.

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:29.490
That's the average value of f.

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:33.610
Now, so this is going to
permit me to make the

00:04:33.610 --> 00:04:37.110
comparison between the mean
value theorem, which we don't

00:04:37.110 --> 00:04:38.630
have stated yet here.

00:04:38.630 --> 00:04:41.010
And the fundamental theorem.

00:04:41.010 --> 00:04:49.130
And I'll do it in the form
of inequalities.

00:04:49.130 --> 00:04:51.550
So right in the middle here,
I'm going to put the

00:04:51.550 --> 00:04:52.370
fundamental theorem.

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:57.070
It says that delta F in this
notation is equal to, well if

00:04:57.070 --> 00:05:00.650
I multiply by delta x again, I
can write it as the average of

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:04.870
F. So I'm going to write it
as the average of F' here.

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:07.100
Times delta x.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:10.790
So we have this factor here,
which is the average of F', or

00:05:10.790 --> 00:05:13.810
the average of little f,
it's the same thing.

00:05:13.810 --> 00:05:15.430
And then I multiplied
through again.

00:05:15.430 --> 00:05:20.810
So I put the thing
in the red box.

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:29.970
Here.

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:37.190
Isn't what the average
of big F.

00:05:37.190 --> 00:05:41.370
So the question is, why is this
the average of little f

00:05:41.370 --> 00:05:47.030
rather than the average of big
F. So the average of a

00:05:47.030 --> 00:05:50.130
function is the typical value.

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:56.520
If, for example, little f were
constant, little f were

00:05:56.520 --> 00:06:01.260
constant, then this integral
would be, so the question is

00:06:01.260 --> 00:06:03.920
why is this the average.

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:08.970
And I'll take a little second
to explain that.

00:06:08.970 --> 00:06:13.050
But I think I'll explain
it over here.

00:06:13.050 --> 00:06:19.010
Because I'm going to erase it.

00:06:19.010 --> 00:06:27.270
So the idea of an average
is the following.

00:06:27.270 --> 00:06:32.281
For example, imagine that
a = 0 and b = n,

00:06:32.281 --> 00:06:33.600
let's say for example.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:46.850
And so we might sum the
function from 1 to n.

00:06:46.850 --> 00:06:49.520
Now, that would be the sum of
the values from 1 to n.

00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:54.960
But the average is, we
divide by n here.

00:06:54.960 --> 00:06:56.140
So this is the average.

00:06:56.140 --> 00:07:01.760
And this is a kind of Riemann
sum, representing the integral

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:06.290
from 0 to n, of f (x) dx.

00:07:06.290 --> 00:07:10.700
Where the increment,
delta x, is 1.

00:07:10.700 --> 00:07:13.470
So this is the notion of
an average value here.

00:07:13.470 --> 00:07:15.840
But in the continuum setting
as opposed to

00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:20.570
the discrete setting.

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:24.870
Whereas what's on the
left-hand side is

00:07:24.870 --> 00:07:26.840
the change in f.

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:31.790
The capital F. And this is the
average of the little f.

00:07:31.790 --> 00:07:33.860
So an average is a sum.

00:07:33.860 --> 00:07:39.520
And it's like an integral.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:42.720
So, in other words what I have
here is that the change in f

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:46.250
is the average of its
infinitesimal change times the

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:50.000
amount of time elapsed,
if you like.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:56.100
So this is the statement of
the fundamental theorem.

00:07:56.100 --> 00:07:56.960
Just rewritten.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:07:58.450
Exactly what I wrote there.

00:07:58.450 --> 00:08:01.780
But I multiplied back
by delta x.

00:08:01.780 --> 00:08:07.530
Now, let me compare this with
the mean value theorem.

00:08:07.530 --> 00:08:13.590
The mean values theorem
also is an equation.

00:08:13.590 --> 00:08:16.420
The mean value theorem says
that this is equal to

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:21.560
F' (c) delta x.

00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:23.270
Now, I pulled a fast
one on you.

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:26.560
I used capital F's here to
make the analogy clear.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:30.800
But the role of the letter
is important to make the

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:32.200
transition to this comparison.

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:35.010
We're talking about the function
capital F here.

00:08:35.010 --> 00:08:36.620
And its derivative.

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:38.510
Now, this is true.

00:08:38.510 --> 00:08:42.510
So now I claim that this thing
is fairly specific.

00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:47.750
Whereas this, unfortunately,
is a little bit vague.

00:08:47.750 --> 00:08:51.360
And the reason why it's vague is
that c is just somewhere in

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:52.790
the interval.

00:08:52.790 --> 00:09:01.010
So some c - sorry, this is some
c, in between a and b.

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:04.930
So really, since we don't know
where this thing is, we don't

00:09:04.930 --> 00:09:07.690
know which of the values it is,
we can't say what it is.

00:09:07.690 --> 00:09:12.410
All we can do is say well for
sure it's less than the

00:09:12.410 --> 00:09:13.280
largest value.

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:18.090
Say, (the maximum
of F' ) delta x.

00:09:18.090 --> 00:09:21.010
And the only thing we can say
for sure on the other end is

00:09:21.010 --> 00:09:24.410
that it's less than or equal to
- sorry, it's greater than

00:09:24.410 --> 00:09:27.410
or equal to, (the minimum
of F' ) delta x.

00:09:27.410 --> 00:09:29.090
Over that same interval.

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:39.650
This is over 0 less than
- sorry, a &lt; x &lt; b.

00:09:39.650 --> 00:09:42.110
So that means that the
fundamental theorem of

00:09:42.110 --> 00:09:45.950
calculus is a much more
specific thing.

00:09:45.950 --> 00:09:48.460
And indeed it gives the
same conclusion.

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:50.230
It's much stronger than the
mean value theorem.

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:52.330
It's way better than the
mean value theorem.

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:56.410
In fact, as soon as we have
integrals, we can abandon the

00:09:56.410 --> 00:09:57.280
mean value theorem.

00:09:57.280 --> 00:09:58.550
We don't want it.

00:09:58.550 --> 00:10:00.810
It's too simple-minded.

00:10:00.810 --> 00:10:03.860
And what we have is something
much more sophisticated, which

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:04.940
we can use.

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:05.760
Which is this.

00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:08.940
So it's obvious that if this is
the average, the average is

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:09.960
less than the maximum.

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:15.190
So it's obvious that it works
just as well to draw this

00:10:15.190 --> 00:10:15.950
conclusion.

00:10:15.950 --> 00:10:20.010
And similarly over here
with the minimum.

00:10:20.010 --> 00:10:22.910
OK, the average is always bigger
than the minimum and

00:10:22.910 --> 00:10:25.430
smaller than the max.

00:10:25.430 --> 00:10:28.680
So this is the connection,
if you like.

00:10:28.680 --> 00:10:32.660
And I'm going to elaborate
just one step further by

00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:36.340
talking about the problem that
you had on the exam.

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:39.640
So there was an Exam
2 problem.

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:43.590
And I'll show you how it works
using the mean value theorem

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:45.610
and how it works using
integrals.

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:48.880
But I'm going to have to use
this notation capital F. So

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:52.450
capital F', as opposed to the
little f, which was what was

00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:55.270
the notation that was
on your exam.

00:10:55.270 --> 00:10:57.620
So we had this situation here.

00:10:57.620 --> 00:11:01.380
These were the givens
of the problem.

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:11.870
And then the question was, the
mean value theorem says, or

00:11:11.870 --> 00:11:14.160
implies, if you like,
it doesn't say it,

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:20.110
but it implies it.

00:11:20.110 --> 00:11:38.690
Implies a &lt; capital F ( 4)
&lt; b, for which a and b?

00:11:38.690 --> 00:11:43.330
So let's take a look
at what it says.

00:11:43.330 --> 00:11:53.620
Well, the mean value theorem
says that F( 4) - F (0) = F' (

00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:57.240
c)( 4 - 0).

00:11:57.240 --> 00:12:03.770
This is this (F') delta x,
this is the change in x.

00:12:03.770 --> 00:12:12.750
And that's the same thing
as (1 / 1 + c )( 4).

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:21.060
And so the range of values of
this number here is from (1 /

00:12:21.060 --> 00:12:24.630
1 plus 0)( 4), that's 4.

00:12:24.630 --> 00:12:28.000
To, that's the largest value, to
the smallest that it gets,

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.510
which is (1 / 1 + 4)( 4).

00:12:32.510 --> 00:12:41.020
That's the range.

00:12:41.020 --> 00:12:53.780
And so the conclusion is that
F (4) - f ( 0 ) is between,

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:55.090
well, let's see.

00:12:55.090 --> 00:12:59.040
It's between 4 and 4/5.

00:12:59.040 --> 00:13:01.850
Which are those two numbers
down there.

00:13:01.850 --> 00:13:04.680
And if you remember that F ( 0)
was 1, this is the same as

00:13:04.680 --> 00:13:15.680
F ( 4), is between 5 and 9/5.

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:19.740
So that's the way that you were
supposed to solve the

00:13:19.740 --> 00:13:22.570
problem on the exam.

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:26.490
On the other hand, let's compare
to what you would do

00:13:26.490 --> 00:13:31.140
with the fundamental theorem
of calculus.

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:33.680
With the fundamentals theorem
of calculus, we have the

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:34.900
following formula.

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:46.100
F( 4) - F ( 0) = the integral
from 0 to 4 of dx / 1 + x.

00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:52.700
That's what the fundamental
theorem says.

00:13:52.700 --> 00:13:56.920
And now I claim that we can
get these same types of

00:13:56.920 --> 00:14:00.780
results by a very elementary
observation.

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:02.820
It's really the same observation
that I made up

00:14:02.820 --> 00:14:06.110
here, that the average is less
than or equal to the maximum.

00:14:06.110 --> 00:14:11.810
Which is that the biggest this
can ever be is, let's see.

00:14:11.810 --> 00:14:15.280
The biggest it is when
x is 0, that's 1.

00:14:15.280 --> 00:14:20.360
So the biggest it ever
gets is this.

00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:25.110
And that's equal to 4.

00:14:25.110 --> 00:14:25.660
Right?

00:14:25.660 --> 00:14:30.910
On the other hand, the smallest
it ever gets to be,

00:14:30.910 --> 00:14:36.770
it's equal to this.

00:14:36.770 --> 00:14:39.800
The smallest it ever gets to
be is the integral from

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:42.400
0 to 4 of 1/5 dx.

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:44.220
Because that's the
lowest value that

00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:46.110
the integrand takes.

00:14:46.110 --> 00:14:48.390
When x = 4, it's 1/5.

00:14:48.390 --> 00:14:54.270
And that's equal to 4/5.

00:14:54.270 --> 00:14:57.720
Now, there's a little tiny
detail which is that really we

00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:00.390
know that this is the area of
some rectangle and this is

00:15:00.390 --> 00:15:01.560
strictly smaller.

00:15:01.560 --> 00:15:03.520
And we know that these
inequalities

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:05.210
are actually strict.

00:15:05.210 --> 00:15:07.620
But that's a minor point.

00:15:07.620 --> 00:15:12.270
And certainly not one that we'll
pay close attention to.

00:15:12.270 --> 00:15:17.910
But now, let me show you what
this looks like geometrically.

00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:19.700
So geometrically, we interpret
this as the

00:15:19.700 --> 00:15:22.270
area under a curve.

00:15:22.270 --> 00:15:31.850
Here's a piece of the
curve y = 1/1 + x.

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:37.130
And it's going up to 4 and
starting at 0 here.

00:15:37.130 --> 00:15:42.570
And the first estimate that we
made; that is, the upper

00:15:42.570 --> 00:15:53.200
bound, was by trapping this in
this big rectangle here.

00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:56.640
We compared it to the constant
function, which was 1 all the

00:15:56.640 --> 00:15:57.990
way across.

00:15:57.990 --> 00:16:00.300
This is y = 1.

00:16:00.300 --> 00:16:06.060
And then we also trapped it
from underneath by the

00:16:06.060 --> 00:16:08.600
function which was
at the bottom.

00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:14.430
And this was y = 1/5.

00:16:14.430 --> 00:16:19.980
And so what this really is is,
these things are the simplest

00:16:19.980 --> 00:16:21.060
possible Riemann sum.

00:16:21.060 --> 00:16:22.860
Sort of a silly Riemann sum.

00:16:22.860 --> 00:16:34.390
This is a Riemann sum
with one rectangle.

00:16:34.390 --> 00:16:36.420
This is the simplest
possible one.

00:16:36.420 --> 00:16:38.580
And so this is a very,
very crude estimate.

00:16:38.580 --> 00:16:40.970
You can see it misses
by a mile.

00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:43.180
The larger and the smaller
values are off

00:16:43.180 --> 00:16:46.370
by a factor of 5.

00:16:46.370 --> 00:16:49.480
But this one is called
the, this one is the

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:53.390
lower Riemann sum.

00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:59.560
And that one is less than
our actual integral.

00:16:59.560 --> 00:17:14.100
Which is less than the
upper Riemann sum.

00:17:14.100 --> 00:17:18.740
And you should, by now, have
looked at those upper and

00:17:18.740 --> 00:17:20.670
lower sums on your homework.

00:17:20.670 --> 00:17:22.630
So it's just the rectangles
underneath and the

00:17:22.630 --> 00:17:25.390
rectangles on top.

00:17:25.390 --> 00:17:28.150
So at this point, we can
literally abandon the mean

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:28.730
value theorem.

00:17:28.730 --> 00:17:30.930
Because we have a much better
way of getting at things.

00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:33.330
If we chop things up into more
rectangles, we'll get much

00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:35.550
better numerical
approximations.

00:17:35.550 --> 00:17:38.640
And if we use simpleminded
expressions with integrals,

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:40.940
we'll be able to figure out any
bound we could get using

00:17:40.940 --> 00:17:42.610
the mean value theorem.

00:17:42.610 --> 00:17:45.790
So that's not the relevance
of the mean value theorem.

00:17:45.790 --> 00:17:49.070
I'll explain to you why we
talked about it, even, in a

00:17:49.070 --> 00:17:51.310
few minutes.

00:17:51.310 --> 00:18:00.040
OK, are there any questions
before we go on?

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:00.290
Yeah.

